  <section line_height="10.87" font="HGIOAZ+CMR12" letter_ratio="0.19"
year_ratio="0.07" cap_ratio="0.69" name_ratio="0.3448275862068966"
word_count="29" lateness="0.05" reference_score="21.2">
    <line x_offset="154.92" y_offset="74.9"
spacing="0.0">&#x2020;&#x2217;</line>
    <line x_offset="258.6" y_offset="74.9" spacing="-7.32">&#x2020;</line>
    <line x_offset="68.76" y_offset="69.84" spacing="-5.81">Masao Iwamatsu
and Yutaka Okabe</line>
    <line x_offset="22.68" y_offset="18.98" spacing="43.54">&#x2020;</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="55.8" spacing="-47.69">Department of
Computer Engineering, Hiroshima City University</line>
    <line x_offset="96.24" y_offset="41.88" spacing="3.05">Hiroshima
731-3194, Japan</line>
    <line x_offset="156.36" y_offset="27.96" spacing="3.05">and</line>
    <line x_offset="26.88" y_offset="13.92" spacing="3.17">Department of
Physics, Tokyo Metropolitan University</line>
    <line x_offset="81.96" y_offset="0.0" spacing="3.05">Hachioji, Tokyo
192-0397, Japan</line>
    <component x="139.32" y="477.07" width="336.06" height="82.22" page="1"
page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
  </section>
  <section line_height="9.96" font="KCQPMK+CMR10" letter_ratio="0.04"
year_ratio="0.0" cap_ratio="0.15" name_ratio="0.2948717948717949"
word_count="78" lateness="0.05" reference_score="16.79">
    <line x_offset="14.88" y_offset="83.76" spacing="0.0">A new Monte Carlo
scheme based on the system of Tsallis's gener-</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="71.76" spacing="2.04">alized statistical
mechanics is applied to a simple double well potential</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="59.76" spacing="2.04">to calculate the
canonical thermal average of potential energy. Al-</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="47.88" spacing="1.92">though we observed
serious quasi-ergodicity when using the standard</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="35.88" spacing="2.04">Metropolis Monte
Carlo algorithm, this problem is largely reduced by</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="23.88" spacing="2.04">the use of the new
Monte Carlo algorithm. Therefore the ergodicity is</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="12.0" spacing="1.92">guaranteed even for
short Monte Carlo steps if we use this new canon-</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="0.0" spacing="2.04">ical Monte Carlo
scheme.</line>
    <component x="153.12" y="322.71" width="304.23" height="93.72" page="1"
page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
  </section>
  <section line_height="10.91" font="KCQPMK+CMR10" letter_ratio="0.05"
year_ratio="0.0" cap_ratio="0.08" name_ratio="0.2490842490842491"
word_count="273" lateness="0.1" reference_score="15.87">
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="325.08" spacing="0.0">The ergodic
hypothesis is fundamental to statistical mechanics. This hy-</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="311.52" spacing="2.65">pothesis states
that the time average of an observable event equals the</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="298.08" spacing="2.53">phase-space
average. In practical application, however, problems can arise</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="284.52" spacing="2.65">in various types
of simulations if the system must overcome high energy</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="270.96" spacing="2.65">barriers to reach
other regions of phase space. In that case, the length</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="257.4" spacing="2.65">of a simulation
needed in order to obtain enough statistical samples of all</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="243.84" spacing="2.65">regions of phase
space may be extremely long. In the Monte Carlo simu-</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="230.28" spacing="2.65">lation, the
errors arise as a consequence of the finite length of the Monte</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="216.72" spacing="2.65">Carlo walk. This
error can be serious in canonical Monte Carlo sampling,</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="203.16" spacing="2.65">especially at low
temperatures. This problem, referred as "quasi-ergodicity"</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="189.6" spacing="2.65">by Valleau and
Whittington [1], appears even in the simplest double well</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="176.04" spacing="2.65">problem, where
the two wells are separated by a large barrier [2].</line>
    <line x_offset="16.92" y_offset="162.48" spacing="2.65">Recently
several authors [3, 4, 5] have proposed a generalized simulated</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="149.04" spacing="2.53">annealing method
to locate the global minimum based on the generalized</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="135.48" spacing="2.65">statistical
mechanics proposed by Tsallis [6], which can overcome the slow</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="121.92" spacing="2.65">convergence of
the traditional simulated annealing method [7] based on the</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="108.36" spacing="2.65">standard Monte
Carlo scheme. Subsequently, Andricioaei and Straub have</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="94.8" spacing="2.65">pointed out that
their generalized Monte Carlo (Tsallis Monte Carlo) [8]</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="81.24" spacing="2.65">method may be used
to overcome the quasi-ergodicity appearing in the</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="67.68" spacing="2.65">canonical average
at constant temperatures.</line>
    <line x_offset="16.92" y_offset="54.12" spacing="2.65">In this short
note we use a new Monte Carlo scheme [8, 9, 10] based</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="40.56" spacing="2.65">on Tsallis's
generalized statistical mechanics [4] for the calculation of the</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="27.0" spacing="2.65">thermal average of
the potential energy of a simple double well potential at</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="13.44" spacing="2.65">constant
temperatures. We examine the performance of this new algorithm</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="0.0" spacing="2.53">designed to overcome
the quasi-ergodicity.</line>
    <component x="125.76" y="293.07" width="358.74" height="335.99"
page="2" page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
  </section>
  <section line_height="10.91" font="KCQPMK+CMR10" letter_ratio="0.07"
year_ratio="0.0" cap_ratio="0.08" name_ratio="0.19128329297820823"
word_count="413" lateness="0.15" reference_score="16.74">
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="114.13" spacing="0.0">In the generalized
statistical mechanics proposed by Tsallis [6], a crucial role</line>
    <line x_offset="182.04" y_offset="99.63" spacing="6.54">q</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="100.57" spacing="-11.85">is played by
the generalized entropy S defined as</line>
    <line x_offset="211.32" y_offset="82.83" spacing="9.78">q</line>
    <line x_offset="174.72" y_offset="76.69" spacing="-4.77">1</line>
    <line x_offset="205.8" y_offset="76.69" spacing="-10.91">p</line>
    <line x_offset="211.32" y_offset="74.31" spacing="-5.58">i</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="69.37" spacing="-5.97">(1)</line>
    <line x_offset="141.72" y_offset="69.37" spacing="-10.91">S = k</line>
    <line x_offset="182.52" y_offset="68.95"
spacing="-18.23">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="148.44" y_offset="68.43" spacing="-7.45">q</line>
    <line x_offset="193.44" y_offset="63.72" spacing="-19.19">(</line>
    <line x_offset="183.24" y_offset="61.81" spacing="-9.0">q 1</line>
    <line x_offset="190.92" y_offset="54.07"
spacing="-10.91">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="40.21" spacing="2.95">where q is a real
number which characterizes the statistical mechanics, and</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="26.65" spacing="2.65">p is the
probability of states i. This entropy S becomes the usual Gibbs-</line>
    <line x_offset="5.52" y_offset="25.71" spacing="-7.03">i</line>
    <line x_offset="227.16" y_offset="25.71" spacing="-7.97">q</line>
    <line x_offset="92.16" y_offset="12.15" spacing="5.59">1</line>
    <line x_offset="147.0" y_offset="12.15" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="168.6" y_offset="12.15" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="112.8" y_offset="5.35" spacing="-11.85">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="213.84" y_offset="5.35"
spacing="-18.65">&#x2192;</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="13.09" spacing="-18.65">Shannon entropy
S = k p ln p when q 1. By maximizing the gen-</line>
    <line x_offset="129.12" y_offset="0.0" spacing="-10.81">(</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="390.71" spacing="0.0">eralized entropy
with the constraints</line>
    <line x_offset="205.08" y_offset="372.24" spacing="10.5">q</line>
    <line x_offset="119.88" y_offset="366.23" spacing="-4.89">p = 1 and p
&#x1EB; = const</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="366.23" spacing="-10.91">(2)</line>
    <line x_offset="125.4" y_offset="365.28" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="214.08" y_offset="365.28" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="205.08" y_offset="363.84" spacing="-6.53">i</line>
    <line x_offset="103.68" y_offset="355.17" spacing="-15.23">(</line>
    <line x_offset="183.36" y_offset="355.17" spacing="-23.9">(</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="341.75" spacing="2.52">where &#x1EB; is
the energy spectrum, the statistical weight for the generalized</line>
    <line x_offset="36.84" y_offset="340.8" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="328.19" spacing="1.71">canonical
ensemble characterized by the parameter q is given by the Tsallis</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="314.63" spacing="2.65">weight</line>
    <line x_offset="136.2" y_offset="305.88" spacing="0.78">q</line>
    <line x_offset="223.56" y_offset="305.04" spacing="-7.13">q</line>
    <line x_offset="210.48" y_offset="299.87" spacing="-5.73">/Z</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="299.87" spacing="-10.91">(3)</line>
    <line x_offset="188.16" y_offset="299.87"
spacing="-10.91">&#x3B2;&#x1EB;</line>
    <line x_offset="130.68" y_offset="299.87" spacing="-10.91">p =
exp</line>
    <line x_offset="199.32" y_offset="298.92" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="222.72" y_offset="297.84" spacing="-6.89">q</line>
    <line x_offset="136.2" y_offset="297.48" spacing="-7.61">i</line>
    <line x_offset="179.64" y_offset="292.12"
spacing="-13.29">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="202.68" y_offset="290.37" spacing="-22.15">(</line>
    <line x_offset="173.76" y_offset="290.37" spacing="-23.9">(</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="278.51" spacing="0.96">with</line>
    <line x_offset="143.04" y_offset="272.39" spacing="-4.79">q</line>
    <line x_offset="168.24" y_offset="264.95" spacing="-3.47">ln 1 (1
q)</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="264.95" spacing="-10.91">(4)</line>
    <line x_offset="102.48" y_offset="264.95" spacing="-10.91">&#x1EB;
=</line>
    <line x_offset="235.2" y_offset="264.95"
spacing="-10.91">&#x3B2;&#x1EB;</line>
    <line x_offset="106.92" y_offset="264.0" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="246.36" y_offset="264.0" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="191.76" y_offset="257.2" spacing="-11.85">&#x2212;
&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="126.0" y_offset="256.79" spacing="-10.49">&#x3B2;(q
1)</line>
    <line x_offset="179.16" y_offset="255.45" spacing="-22.57">(</line>
    <line x_offset="249.72" y_offset="255.45" spacing="-23.9">(</line>
    <line x_offset="144.72" y_offset="249.04"
spacing="-12.24">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="32.04" y_offset="236.99" spacing="1.15">&#x1EB; is the
generalized energy and &#x3B2; is the Lagrange multiplier, which</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="236.99" spacing="-10.91">where</line>
    <line x_offset="36.48" y_offset="236.04" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="223.43" spacing="1.71">plays the role of
the generalized temperature in the Tsallis statistical me-</line>
    <line x_offset="281.04" y_offset="212.47" spacing="3.26">not</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="209.87" spacing="-8.3">chanics. We
should note here that the statistical weight is</line>
    <line x_offset="300.0" y_offset="209.87" spacing="-10.91">given by
the</line>
    <line x_offset="207.12" y_offset="202.32" spacing="-0.42">q</line>
    <line x_offset="131.64" y_offset="198.91" spacing="-4.28">but</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="196.31" spacing="-8.3">probability
distribution p</line>
    <line x_offset="151.08" y_offset="196.31" spacing="-10.91">rather by p
in order to calculate thermal</line>
    <line x_offset="123.36" y_offset="195.36" spacing="-7.03">i</line>
    <line x_offset="207.12" y_offset="193.92" spacing="-6.53">i</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="182.75" spacing="0.27">averages, as can
be seen in (2). The generalized canonical partition function</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="169.19" spacing="2.65">Z in (3) is given
by</line>
    <line x_offset="7.44" y_offset="168.24" spacing="-7.02">q</line>
    <line x_offset="200.76" y_offset="153.35" spacing="3.99">&#x3B2;&#x1EB;
/q</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="153.35" spacing="-10.91">(5)</line>
    <line x_offset="125.04" y_offset="153.35" spacing="-10.91">Z =
exp</line>
    <line x_offset="211.92" y_offset="152.4" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="132.48" y_offset="152.4" spacing="-7.97">q</line>
    <line x_offset="192.24" y_offset="145.6"
spacing="-11.85">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="225.96" y_offset="143.85" spacing="-22.15">(</line>
    <line x_offset="186.24" y_offset="143.85" spacing="-23.9">(</line>
    <line x_offset="151.56" y_offset="142.29" spacing="-22.34">(</line>
    <line x_offset="104.4" y_offset="130.07" spacing="1.32">&#x1EB;</line>
    <line x_offset="134.16" y_offset="130.07" spacing="-10.91">&#x1EB; and
&#x3B2; &#x3B2; = 1/kT where T is the usual</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="130.07" spacing="-10.91">In the limit
q</line>
    <line x_offset="90.36" y_offset="130.07" spacing="-10.91">1,</line>
    <line x_offset="108.72" y_offset="129.12" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="138.6" y_offset="129.12" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="117.72" y_offset="122.32"
spacing="-11.85">&#x2192;</line>
    <line x_offset="182.16" y_offset="122.32"
spacing="-18.65">&#x2192;</line>
    <line x_offset="73.92" y_offset="122.32"
spacing="-18.65">&#x2192;</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="116.51" spacing="-5.09">temperature
[11], then the Tsallis weight (3) becomes the Boltamann weight</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="102.95" spacing="2.65">p = exp(
&#x3B2;&#x1EB; )/Z of the usual canonical ensemble.</line>
    <line x_offset="5.52" y_offset="102.0" spacing="-7.02">i</line>
    <line x_offset="63.96" y_offset="102.0" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="83.88" y_offset="102.0" spacing="-7.97">1</line>
    <line x_offset="44.28" y_offset="95.2" spacing="-11.85">&#x2212;</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="51.35" spacing="32.95">(6)</line>
    <line x_offset="344.76" y_offset="2.39" spacing="38.05">(7)</line>
    <line x_offset="16.92" y_offset="89.39" spacing="-97.91">In this
generalized statistical mechanics, Andricioaei and Straub [5] have</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="75.83" spacing="2.65">noted that since
the average of an observable O is defined by</line>
    <line x_offset="205.08" y_offset="57.36" spacing="10.5">q</line>
    <line x_offset="135.6" y_offset="51.35" spacing="-4.89">&lt; O &gt; = p
O ,</line>
    <line x_offset="167.28" y_offset="50.4" spacing="-7.02">q</line>
    <line x_offset="217.92" y_offset="50.4" spacing="-7.97">i</line>
    <line x_offset="205.08" y_offset="48.96" spacing="-6.53">i</line>
    <line x_offset="183.36" y_offset="40.29" spacing="-15.23">(</line>
    <line x_offset="207.0" y_offset="1.44" spacing="30.88">ji</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="26.87" spacing="-36.33">the detailed
balance condition should be written as</line>
    <line x_offset="150.0" y_offset="8.4" spacing="10.5">q</line>
    <line x_offset="192.12" y_offset="8.4" spacing="-7.97">q</line>
    <line x_offset="164.88" y_offset="1.44" spacing="-1.01">ij</line>
    <line x_offset="150.0" y_offset="0.0" spacing="-6.53">i</line>
    <line x_offset="144.48" y_offset="2.39" spacing="-13.29">p W = p
W</line>
    <line x_offset="192.12" y_offset="0.0" spacing="-5.58">j</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="67.8" spacing="0.0">where W is the
element of the transition matrix. Based on this observation,</line>
    <line x_offset="40.92" y_offset="66.85" spacing="-7.02">ij</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="54.24" spacing="1.71">they [5] pointed
out that the generalized Monte Carlo algorithm [4] originally</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="40.68" spacing="2.65">proposed by Penna
[3] in his generalized simulated annealing method cannot</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="27.12" spacing="2.65">satisfy the
detailed balance. They [5] then proposed a new generalized Monte</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="13.56" spacing="2.65">Carlo scheme,
where the acceptance probability p of the Monte Carlo move</line>
    <line x_offset="0.0" y_offset="0.0" spacing="2.65">is given by</line>
    <component x="125.76" y="120.14" width="358.75" height="125.04"
page="2" page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
    <component x="125.76" y="251.81" width="358.84" height="401.61"
page="3" page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
    <component x="125.76" y="161.91" width="358.62" height="78.71" page="3"
page_width="612.0" page_height="792.0"/>
  </section>
  <section line_height="10.91" font="KCQPMK+CMR10" letter_ratio="0.1"
